On 8/6/10 2:26 AM, HyuuGaBaDita wrote:
&gt; Hi Gordon,
&gt; Once again want to thank you for your fast reply! You are great!
&gt; I still facing some problem when I am using heritrix:
&gt; 1.Why is it take me a very long time to archive a website even though I already set the depth and hosts to vry minimun:1 or 2 level.
&gt; 2. Why is it sometimes the archived progress reach till 99% and it will hang there then it take long hours to finished.

Reviewing and understanding the &#39;threads&#39; and &#39;frontier&#39; reports can 
help explain why a crawler is progressing as expected, or not. Also, you 
may find the FAQ helpful:

https://webarchive.jira.com/wiki/display/Heritrix/crawl+rate+considerations

&gt; 3. Can we avoid to fill in the http-header-user agent and provide the email address... or can we preset it instead of every time when I archived, I need to fill it in.

No; each job must be configured with acceptable values here. By starting 
your new configurations with a copy of a prior configuration, you won&#39;t 
have to reenter the values every time.

&gt; 4.Can I categorized my archived work? Say,
&gt; Education website: www.abc.com, www.bcd.com, www.efg.com
&gt; Goverment website: www.xyz.com, www.hij.com, www.klm.com
&gt; Music website: www.lmn.com, www.opq.com

There is no built-in feature for this; you would have to code it yourself.

&gt; 5. Can heritrix perform scheduling task? This is beacuase every 2 months I need to re-archive the same websites, IS it possible to automate it, so that every 2 month it will auto acrchive the websites.

Advanced users can manage this in a few ways. The only info is on the 
wiki and in the source code, about repeating a crawl with certain 
history date from the earlier crawls used to avoid refetching or 
restoring duplicate content. (Look for &quot;Duplication Reduction&quot; info.)

Are you on the same project as &#39;Allen Wilson&#39;/&#39;Allen Sim&#39;? Your 
questions are very similar in rapid succession, and even similarly 
worded. It&#39;s always good to review recent mail list traffic and search 
the archives to see if your questions have already been asked/answered.

- Gordon @ IA

